    "name" : "Lake Ice-Out Lesson 1 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"ice-out day\",\"definition\":\"The day of the year in which ice cover leaves a lake. The Maine Department of Agriculture, Forestry, and Conservation defines ice-out as “when you can navigate unimpeded from one end of the water body to the other. There may still be ice in coves or along the shoreline in some areas, but when a person can traverse the entire waterbody without being stopped by ice floes we will consider the ice to be out.”\"}]}",
