    "name" : "The Shape of Change Lesson 1 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"global temperature\",\"definition\":\"An average of temperatures taken at different places all around the world—all the hot places, all the cold places, and all the places in between. To get a single global temperature for one year, scientists add up the average temperature measurements from each day and divide the total by 365 days.\"},{\"word\":\"average\",\"definition\":\"A calculated \"central\" value of a set of numbers. To calculate it: add up all the numbers, then divide by how many numbers there are.\"},{\"word\":\"data table\",\"definition\":\"A display of related information arranged in labeled rows and columns.\"},{\"word\":\"ascending\",\"definition\":\"Increasing or going up.\"},{\"word\":\"time series graph\",\"definition\":\"A graph of repeated measurements taken over regular time intervals. Time series graphs are useful for visualizing how something changes over time. In a time series graph, time is always plotted on the x-axis.\"},{\"word\":\"x-axis\",\"definition\":\"The horizontal axis on a graph that goes from left to right.\"},{\"word\":\"y-axis\",\"definition\":\"The vertical axis on a graph that goes up and down.\"},{\"word\":\"line of best fit\",\"definition\":\"A straight line drawn through data to show the general direction of change over time. This line usually won’t touch all the points, but it will come as close as possible. Often called a trend line or least squares line.\"},{\"word\":\"Least Squares Line\",\"definition\":\"See line of best fit.\"},{\"word\":\"trend\",\"definition\":\"A description of the overall direction of change over time of the data on a time series graph.\"}]}",
