    "name" : "The Shape of Change Lesson 2 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"climate\",\"definition\":\"The average weather in a place over many years. Scientists typically use a period of 30 years to determine climate conditions for specified region.\"},{\"word\":\"steepness\",\"definition\":\"A measure of how slanted a line is.\"},{\"word\":\"model\",\"definition\":\"A tool that scientists use to make predictions based on what they observe in data. Models can be represented in many ways. For example, trend lines and forecasts are types of \"mathematical models.\"\"},{\"word\":\"forecast\",\"definition\":\"An extension of the past into the future. For data, this means extending a trend line from data that have already been collected to estimate what is likely to occur in the future (assuming that things continue to change at the same rate).\"},{\"word\":\"dot plot\",\"definition\":\"A type of graph that shows each data point as a dot above a number line. Dot plots are good for comparing data values and visualizing the range of a data set.\"},{\"word\":\"range\",\"definition\":\"The difference between the highest and the lowest values of a data set.\"}]}",
