    "name" : "Ticks & Lyme Disease Lesson 1 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"Lyme disease\",\"definition\":\"An infection caused by bacteria that is transmitted to humans through the bite of an infected blacklegged tick. Typical symptoms include fever, headache, fatigue, and a characteristic skin rash called “erythema migrans.”\"},{\"word\":\"blacklegged tick\",\"definition\":\"A hard-bodied tick commonly known as the deer tick. Blacklegged ticks can transmit Lyme disease to humans through their bite.\"},{\"word\":\"Erythema migrans\",\"definition\":\"An expanding bullseye-shaped rash often seen in the early stage of Lyme disease. The name means \"migrating redness\"in Latin.\"},{\"word\":\"repellent\",\"definition\":\"A substance that keeps ticks and insects away.\"}]}",
