    "name" : "Ticks & Lyme Disease Lesson 2 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"incidence\",\"definition\":\"See rate.\"},{\"word\":\"rate\",\"definition\":\"A measure of how many new (or newly diagnosed) cases of Lyme disease there are each year per 100,000 people, so that we can make meaningful comparisons between places with high, medium, or low populations. Also called incidence.\"},{\"word\":\"ascending\",\"definition\":\"Increasing or going up.\"},{\"word\":\"time series graph\",\"definition\":\"A graph of repeated measurements taken over regular time intervals. Time series graphs are useful for visualizing how something changes over time. In a time series graph, time is always plotting on the x-axis.\"},{\"word\":\"trend\",\"definition\":\"A description of the overall direction of change over time of the data on a time series graph.\"},{\"word\":\"line of best fit\",\"definition\":\"A straight line drawn through data to show the general direction of change over time. This line usually won’t touch all the points, but it will come as close as possible. Often called a trend line or least squares line.\"},{\"word\":\"Least Squares Line\",\"definition\":\"See line of best fit.\"}]}",
