    "id" : 20,
    "name" : "Ticks & Lyme Disease Lesson 3 Glossary",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":true,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"host\",\"definition\":\"An animal on which a tick feeds. Common hosts for blacklegged ticks are mice, deer, and humans.\"},{\"word\":\"questing\",\"definition\":\"When a tick holds onto leaves or grass waiting to climb onto a person or animal.\"},{\"word\":\"nymph\",\"definition\":\"The stage of a blacklegged tick’s life cycle between larva and adult. It is during this stage that ticks are most likely to transmit Lyme disease to humans.\"},{\"word\":\"life cycle\",\"definition\":\"The series of stages through which a tick passes during its lifetime.The lifecycle of blacklegged ticks generally lasts two years. During this time, they go through four life stages: egg, six-legged larva, eight-legged nymph, and adult. After the eggs hatch, the ticks must have a blood meal at every stage to survive.\"},{\"word\":\"dot plot\",\"definition\":\"A type of graph that shows each data point as a dot above a number line. Dot plots are good for comparing data values and visualizing the range of a data set.\"},{\"word\":\"range\",\"definition\":\"The difference between the highest and the lowest values of a data set.\"},{\"word\":\"model\",\"definition\":\"A tool that scientists use to make predictions based on what they observe in data. Models can be represented in many ways. For example, trend lines and forecasts are types of \"mathematical models.\"\"},{\"word\":\"forecast\",\"definition\":\"An extension of the past into the future. For data, this means extending a trend line from data that have already been collected to estimate what is likely to occur in the future (assuming that things continue to change at the same rate).\"},{\"word\":\"average\",\"definition\":\"A calculated \"central\" value of a set of numbers. To calculate it: add up all the numbers, then divide by how many numbers there are. \"}]}",
