    "name" : "heat and temperature",
    "json" : "{\"askForUserDefinition\":false,\"autoShowMediaInPopup\":false,\"showSideBar\":true,\"enableStudentRecording\":false,\"definitions\":[{\"word\":\"average kinetic energy\",\"definition\":\"The average kinetic energy is the total kinetic energy divided by the number of atoms.\"},{\"word\":\"it often responds with a temperature rise\",\"definition\":\"There are exceptions. For example, adding energy to ice at the melting point causes it to melt but the temperature does not rise.\"},{\"word\":\"femtosecond\",\"definition\":\"A femtosecond is 10^(-15) second. This is about the time it takes a hydrogen atom to move a distance comparable to its radius. \"},{\"word\":\"energy unit on the bar graphs\",\"definition\":\"It is convenient to measure energy at the atomic scale in units of electron volt which is abbreviated eV. Electron volt is a unit of energy, like Joules, but far smaller.\"},{\"word\":\"isolated from the rest of the world\",\"definition\":\"When a system does not exchange energy or matter with the surrounding environment, it is considered isolated from the rest of the world. Such a system is called an isolated system.\"},{\"word\":\"note 1\",\"definition\":\"Although most materials expand when heated, there are some exceptional materials that actually contract within a certain temperature range. This is called negative thermal expansion.\"},{\"word\":\"random motion\",\"definition\":\"When you throw a Frisbee, all of its atoms move at the same speed in the same direction at any time during its flying course. This kind of movement is not related to temperature, as it is not random.\"}]}",
